Introduction ¶

This Jupyter Notebook is meant to conduct the anaylsis as well as to present the results of the atomic spectroscopy lab. Generally all code provided is a guideline in order to get your analysis started. In case you want to use your own methods, feel free to change as much of the code as you like. Each of the three tasks starts with the analysis of the data, followed by some calculations and ends with a discussion. The first task provides a lot of the code needed, whereas in the last part most of the coding is up to you.

Before you can run any part, you need to import the modules below (shift + enter):

1. The spectrum of Hydrogen ¶

1.1 The spectrum of Hydrogen¶

Record a spectrum of the hydrogen lamp using the spectrometer channel with large range. Make sure the measurement is strong, but not saturated. Save the data as ASCII file and transfer them to the computer on which you have your Jupyter Notebook. With the function read from package pandas one loads in the experimental data. To do this, you have to specify the data path and file name accordinlgy in the field below. Please mind that the absolute path must be specified using / instead of \.

In [ ]:
# Specify the absolute path for the hydrogen spectrum inside quotation marks:
df = pd.read_csv(r"Data\H_1804344U2.TXT" , 
    sep=";",    # Here we specify that values are seperated by semicolons.
    header=6,   # This skips the first rows of the file containing information about the acquisiton settings
                 
    # Check if your spectrum txt file contains of 4 or 5 coulumns. If you have 5 coulumns use the adapted 'names'-array the line below.

1.3 Calculate Rydberg constant¶

Use your extracted data to determine an experimental value for the Rydberg constant of hydrogen using the formula from the course book:
$ h \nu = \frac{h c}{\lambda}= R_{H}\left(\frac{1}{n_{1}^{2}}-\frac{1}{n_{2}^{2}}\right)$,
where $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ are two consecutive quantum numbers. Use the empty code box below to write your own code to extract the Rydberg constant.

In [ ]:
## Write your code here to determine the Rydberg constant
h = 6.62607e-34  # J*s
c = 299792458  # m/s
lambd = 656.279e-9  # m
e = 1.602176634e-19  # C
n_1 = 2
n_2 = 3

R1 = (h*c/lambd)/(1/n_1**2-1/n_2**2)/e

print("The Rydberg constant is:", R1, "eV")

#Dubbelkolla med andra peaks
lambd = 486.135e-9	
n_2 = 4
R2 = (h*c/lambd)/(1/n_1**2-1/n_2**2)/e
print("The Rydberg constant is:", R2, "eV")


#Trippelkolla med tredje peaks
lambd = 434.0472e-9	
n_2 = 5
R3 = (h*c/lambd)/(1/n_1**2-1/n_2**2)/e
print("The Rydberg constant is:", R3, "eV")

average_R = (R1 + R2 + R3) / 3
print("The average Rydberg constant is:", average_R, "eV")

The Rydberg constant is: 13.602169013569126 eV
The Rydberg constant is: 13.602228779602582 eV
The average Rydberg constant is: 13.602211388962296 eV

1.4 Discussion ¶

Describe below the procedure (spectrometer settings) used for the experimental determination of result and any difficulties with the measurement, or how to overcome them. Compare the experimental value for the Rydberg constant with literature in a brief text. Perform an error estimation and discuss whether your result is reasonable.

A spectrometer (AvaSpecULS3648-2-USB2) by the company Avantes was connected via USB to a computer. The spectrometer was then placed a distance of 5 cm from the hydrogen lamp. The data from the spectrometer was transferred to the computer via two separate fiber optic cables, each representing a different channel. One of the channels transferred had a grating line density (GRL) of 3600 lines/mm and collected incoming photons with a wavelength between 320 - 370 nm. The other channel had a GRL of 600 lines/mm and was designed to collect photons with a wavelength between 320-840 nm. Both channels had an entrance slit width of 10 um and a resolution of 3648 pixels. These channels were processed by the program Avasoft, which was installed on the aforementioned computer. The integration time during which incoming photons were measured was set to 600 ms and the averaging number of scans collected was 10 times. In order to collect a "dark" spectrum, i.e a spectrum when only the background photons was measured, a red paper was placed in front of the lamp. A spectrum was then collected using the same integration settings as described before.

The spectrum achieved from these measurements can be seen under section 1.4. As one is able to see, the spectrum is quite low quality with a very prominent peak at around 590 nm. Since this peak should not be included in a spectrum from hydrogen we can deduce that the hydrogen lamp had been contaminated. The contamination is most likely from sodium, since it has a peak around 589 nm. Furthermore, due to incompetence, a spectrum that wasn't correct for by the dark spectrum was used throughout most of the calculations in this report. To resolve these problems, one could use another lamp that hasn't been contaminated and take the dark spectrum into account when doing the computations done in the report.

Our average measured value of the Rydberg constant was 10970924 m^-1. The value found in the literature is 10973730 m^-1. This corresponds to a difference of 2806 m^-1 or, as a percentage of the correct value, 0.026%. Therefore, the error is considered to be small. When we calibrated the value we used the incoming wavelength of the photons, which propagated through air. Thus, a conversion between air wavelength and vacuum wavelength was necessary. For this conversion, a conversion coefficient of 1.0003 was utilized. However, this is dependent on the air composition and temperature of the room and therefore this approximation might not be accurate. Another source of error might be the accuracy and calibration of the spectrometer. In summation, an error of this magnitude can depend on various factors and should be disregarded.

2. The quantum defect ¶

Plug in the sodium lamp in the lamp holder and measure a spectrum using the spectrometer channel with large range. Since sodium has a very intense feature, you need to record two spectra with different integration time. The unsaturated spectrum gives the wavelength of the intense line. The saturated spectrum (with the strong line being cut-off) will reveal the less intense features. Focus on the region between 430 and 630 nm when adjusting the intensity, ignoring the strong feature.

Load in the spectrum that is not saturated (the strong feature not being cut off).

import numpy as np
h = 6.62607e-34  # J*s
c = 299792458  # m/s
RH = 1.097e7
l0 = 1.373
e = 1.602176634e-19  
from scipy.optimize import minimize_scalar

def objective(l1):
    wavelength_inverse = RH * (1/(3-l0)**2 - 1/(3-l1)**2)
    wavelength = 1 / wavelength_inverse  # Convert back to wavelength in meters
    return abs(wavelength - sodium_vac_wavelength[0]*1e-9)
bounds = (-10, 10)
result = minimize_scalar(objective, bounds=bounds)
print("Optimized value of l1:", result.x)
l1 = result.x

def objective(l2):
    wavelength_inverse = RH * (1/(3-l1)**2 - 1/(4-l2)**2)
    wavelength = 1 / wavelength_inverse  # Convert back to wavelength in meters
    return abs(wavelength - sodium_vac_wavelength[2]*1e-9)
result = minimize_scalar(objective, bounds=bounds)
print("Optimized value of l2:", result.x)

Estimate the vacuum wavelength for the transition 3p – 8d in sodium as accurately as possible. Enter the formula that you use here (you can write LaTex code):

2.5 Discussion ¶

Describe your procedure (particularly the spectrometer settings) and discuss your results for the quantum defects and the 3p-8d vacuum wavelength in the field below. Compare your result with literature values and do an error estimation. Comment, in particular, on the internal order of the energy levels corresponding to different orbitals, and on the underlying physics. Include a drawing of the energy level diagram of sodium containing the lines that have been observed (Edit > Insert image).

Both of the experiments in this part were made with focus on the 290-860 nm range and averaged of 10 measurements. In the first experiment, we did not saturate the largest peak and for this reason we only needed to integrate over 1,150 ms. In the second experiment we wanted to look at other peaks, and integrated for 600 ms instead, which completely saturated the peak at 590 nm. We did not find a transition corresponding to our peak at 516.02515 nm in the literature, and for this reason we chose to ignore this measurement. We also found that every peak we measured consisted of two peaks, this is because of spin-orbit interactions, and for this assignment we chose to use an average of the two peaks.

We started by concluding that we approximate the impact of n on the quantum defect to 0, so calculations are easier. We then calculated the values for quantum defects by minimizing the absolute value of a wavelength calculated with the quantum defect subtracted by our measured value. This resulted in a good value for l=1 but a poor value for l=2. This is probably because of inaccuracy in measurements, not taking fine structure into account and because we calculated l=2 based on l=1, which in turn was calculated. This introduces an error of the error to our measurements.

When calculating the wavelengths emitted from the 3p-8d transition we once again assumed that the quantum defect only depended on l. This calculation resulted in the wavelength 439.2 nm which is close the the value found in the literature (439.3 nm).

The internal order of the energy levels is apparent in the picture below, the most interesting conclusion is that energies in the l=0 orbital has significantly lower energies than other shells

3.3 Discussion¶

Describe your procedure and discuss your results in field below. Compare your result with literature values and do an error estimation. Furthermore, answer the following points:

  • Include a drawing of the energy level diagram of cadmium containing the observed transitions (Edit > Insert image).
  • There is a hardly visible line around 350 nm. To what energy levels does this transition correspond to? Why is it so weak, and why can we see it at all?
In [ ]:
display(Image(filename='Triplets.png'))

The procedure of this experiment was similar to the one described under 1.4, with a few differences. Mainly, the spectrum from this experiment was taken from a Cadmium lamp instead of a hydrogen one and the wavelength region from channel one was studied in detail (320 - 370 nm). The integration time for this experiment was set to 32 ms and the measurements were averaged over 5 experiments.

Several different spectral lines were studied in detail and their corresponding transitions were looked up in NIST. A fine structure can be identified when looking at the spectrum. The identified transition that revealed the fine structure was 4d105s5d - 4d105s5p. The fine structure, which splits the different J states in energy, is illustrated in the picture above. In order to map out the relative differences in energy resulting from the fine structure the equation which describes the Lande-interval rule was utilized. The relative difference in energy according to the interval rule should be 3/2 for the D-triplet and 2/1 for the P-triplet. The measured interval achieved for the D-triplet was 1.5164 and 2.159 for the P-triplet. Many reasons may lie behind the reason that the Lande interval somehow fails, one of them can be Coulomb interactions between the individual electrons, or some relativistic effect that remains unaccounted for. Another reason can be some form of measuring error on our part. However, both calculated intervals are reasonable and can be considered to lie within the margin of error.

The peak around 350 is visible in our spectrum and can be identified in NIST. It corresponds to a 4d105s5d 1D --> 4d105s5p 3P transition. As one can tell, this transitions involves a change of multiplicity from 1 to 3, which means a change in the quantom number S from 0 to 1. According to the E1 transition rules this is forbidden. As we can see from this experiment, the transition does indeed happen. One can conclude that the transition is most likely not an E1 transition, but rather some other form of transition, which is why the relative intensity of this peak is small. LS coupling works best for smaller atoms, however Cadmium is a medium-sized atom and for this reason jj-coupling might also be needed to understands its behavior.
